jan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Swan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swon(e)</i>, northern Middle English <i>swan(e)</i> ‘swineherd; peasant; male servant’ (Old English <i>swān</i>). Compare   Swain   2, with which this name was thoroughly confused.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>swan</i>, <i>swon</i> ‘swan’. In the Middle Ages, the swan was taken as a symbol of false pride, and, according to Chaucer, jealousy. Compare   Kite  ,   Nightingale  , and   Pye  .","English: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Swan</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>. Compare   Swain   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Swann","meanings":["English: variant of   Swan  ."]},{"name":"Swahn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Lennart.","Swedish: variant of <b>Svan</b>, ornamental name from <i>svan</i> ‘swan’. Compare   Swan  .","Americanized form of German   Schwahn  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Swain","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Swain</i>, <i>Swein</i> (Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>, <i>Sven</i>, from <i>sveinn</i> ‘lad’).","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swein</i> ‘servant, attendant; boy, young man’ (Old Norse <i>sveinn</i>). The word could also denote a swineherd or a peasant in general. The name was thoroughly confused with   Swan   1.","Irish: when not the English name, possibly an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Suibhne</b>; see   McSwain  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes De Swan was born in 1341, in Hodsock, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Sir John de Cressy of Hodsock. She died in 1378, in her hometown, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1341–1378":"1341–1378","1338–1383":"1338–1383","1357–1419":"1357–1419","1370–1408":"1370–1408","1374–1409":"1374–1409","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1341":"1341","1374":"1374","Abt 1357":"umbes 1357","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","1338":"1338","1357":"1357","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","about 1376":"umbes 1376","1409":"1409","23 June 1374":"23. juuni 1374","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","Hodsock, Blyth, Nottingham, England, United Kingdom":"Hodsock, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hodsock, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hodsock, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Gotham, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1341–1378":"1341–1378","1338–1383":"1338–1383","1357–1419":"1357–1419","1370–1408":"1370–1408","1374–1409":"1374–1409","1376–Female":"1376–Kuollut","1341":"1341","1374":"1374","Abt 1357":"noin 1357","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","1338":"1338","1357":"1357","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","about 1376":"noin 1376","1409":"1409","23 June 1374":"23. kesäkuuta 1374","1408